383
00:13:46,658 --> 00:13:48,025
Of course the fact that our
neurons

384
00:13:48,026 --> 00:13:49,393
work through electricity

385
00:13:49,394 --> 00:13:51,962
means that we can also
record from them,

386
00:13:51,963 --> 00:13:54,431
and that has amazing
medical applications.

387
00:13:54,432 --> 00:13:57,301
The electroencephalogram,
or EEG,

388
00:13:57,302 --> 00:13:58,969
came about in the 1920s,

389
00:13:58,970 --> 00:14:01,071
 allowing doctors to see
 some of the brain's

390
00:14:01,072 --> 00:14:03,974
 electrical signals
 as visible brain waves.

391
00:14:03,975 --> 00:14:05,442
 But by the 1980s,

392
00:14:05,443 --> 00:14:07,678
scientists realized
that for some tasks,

393
00:14:07,679 --> 00:14:09,914
like the dream of allowing
paralyzed patients

394
00:14:09,915 --> 00:14:11,348
to move a robotic arm,

395
00:14:11,349 --> 00:14:13,317
you need a much richer
brain signal.

396
00:14:13,318 --> 00:14:14,418
 That's because moving an arm

397
00:14:14,419 --> 00:14:16,220
 requires a lot of information.

398
00:14:16,221 --> 00:14:18,255
 You need information
 for how to move your upper arm,

399
00:14:18,256 --> 00:14:19,657
 your forearm, your hand,

400
00:14:19,658 --> 00:14:22,026
 your fingers,
 all through 3D space.

401
00:14:22,027 --> 00:14:24,528
EEG just doesn't carry enough
information to do that,

402
00:14:24,529 --> 00:14:26,463
since the electrical signals
it picks up

403
00:14:26,464 --> 00:14:28,432
get distorted
after they make their way

404
00:14:28,433 --> 00:14:30,334
through our skull and skin.

405
00:14:30,335 --> 00:14:32,937
So, if you wanted to control
a prosthetic limb

406
00:14:32,938 --> 00:14:35,539
with just your mind,
researchers realized

407
00:14:35,540 --> 00:14:39,076
you'd need to record
directly from the brain.

408
00:14:39,077 --> 00:14:40,344
And in 2006,

409
00:14:40,345 --> 00:14:42,479
scientists finally
did just that.

410
00:14:42,480 --> 00:14:44,181
 They implanted an electrode

411
00:14:44,182 --> 00:14:46,016
 in the brain
 of a paralyzed human

412
00:14:46,017 --> 00:14:47,518
 for the very first time.

413
00:14:47,519 --> 00:14:49,320
 And since that
 first test patient,

414
00:14:49,321 --> 00:14:50,955
 several paralyzed patients

415
00:14:50,956 --> 00:14:52,389
 have received brain implants

416
00:14:52,390 --> 00:14:54,458
 that allow them
 to control robotic arms

417
00:14:54,459 --> 00:14:56,093
 with their minds.

418
00:14:56,094 --> 00:14:59,163
 As our understanding
 of the brain grows

419
00:14:59,164 --> 00:15:00,497
 and our computers get better

420
00:15:00,498 --> 00:15:02,633
 at decoding signals
 from the brain,

421
00:15:02,634 --> 00:15:05,970
 these patients are gaining
 finer and finer control

422
00:15:05,971 --> 00:15:08,372
 over these robotic arms.

423
00:15:08,373 --> 00:15:11,375
 Recently, science has taken
 a big leap forward

424
00:15:11,376 --> 00:15:13,243
 from allowing
 paralyzed patients

425
00:15:13,244 --> 00:15:15,446
 to control robotic limbs

426
00:15:15,447 --> 00:15:18,382
 to giving them control
 of their own limbs.

427
00:15:18,383 --> 00:15:21,618
 I traveled
 to Ohio State University

428
00:15:21,619 --> 00:15:24,555
 to meet one of those patients,
 Ian Burkhart.

429
00:15:24,556 --> 00:15:27,191
 At 19, while vacationing
 with friends,

430
00:15:27,192 --> 00:15:29,326
 Ian dove into a wave
 at the beach

431
00:15:29,327 --> 00:15:31,495
 and broke his neck
 on the sandy floor,

432
00:15:31,496 --> 00:15:35,199
 leaving him paralyzed
 from the chest down.

433
00:15:35,200 --> 00:15:36,700
[Ian] I knew as soon as I hit

434
00:15:36,701 --> 00:15:38,135
that I was paralyzed.

435
00:15:38,136 --> 00:15:40,170
And I was floating
face-down in the water

436
00:15:40,171 --> 00:15:42,039
-and could not get up.
-Could you...

437
00:15:42,040 --> 00:15:43,474
[Ian] I couldn't move
anything at all.

438
00:15:43,475 --> 00:15:45,743
 You go from being 19
 and independent,

439
00:15:45,744 --> 00:15:48,012
 living on your own
 in college, to now.

440
00:15:48,013 --> 00:15:49,713
 I need help doing everything

441
00:15:49,714 --> 00:15:52,649
 from eating to going
 to the bathroom,

442
00:15:52,650 --> 00:15:55,219
 sitting up,
 getting into my wheelchair.

443
00:15:55,220 --> 00:15:56,587
 I can move my shoulders
 pretty well,

444
00:15:56,588 --> 00:15:58,022
can move my biceps
that allow me

445
00:15:58,023 --> 00:15:59,156
to move my arms
a little bit,

446
00:15:59,157 --> 00:16:01,058
but nothing
from my biceps down.

447
00:16:01,059 --> 00:16:03,427
[Michael] The doctors
 at Ohio State had approached

448
00:16:03,428 --> 00:16:06,530
 Ian about a revolutionary
 experimental treatment

449
00:16:06,531 --> 00:16:08,298
 developed by Battelle,

450
00:16:08,299 --> 00:16:09,533
 a research
 and development firm

451
00:16:09,534 --> 00:16:11,235
 using cutting-edge technology

452
00:16:11,236 --> 00:16:12,636
 called NeuroLife.

453
00:16:12,637 --> 00:16:14,538
 They wanted to implant a chip

454
00:16:14,539 --> 00:16:16,206
 in Ian's motor cortex,

455
00:16:16,207 --> 00:16:18,575
 which would allow him
 to move his hand again

456
00:16:18,576 --> 00:16:21,812
 while he was connected
 to a computer in the lab.

457
00:16:21,813 --> 00:16:24,681
 I was invited
