00:18:10,255 --> 00:18:12,422
 contains a hundred
 and thirty electrodes,

510
00:18:12,423 --> 00:18:15,159
 which stimulate the muscles
 in his forearm

511
00:18:15,160 --> 00:18:17,227
 to produce the specific
 movements

512
00:18:17,228 --> 00:18:19,496
 that his brain
 is thinking about,

513
00:18:19,497 --> 00:18:21,298
 such as closing his hand

514
00:18:21,299 --> 00:18:22,933
 or moving his thumb.

515
00:18:22,934 --> 00:18:26,670
 Now it was time to see Ian
 move his paralyzed hand

516
00:18:26,671 --> 00:18:28,305
 with his thoughts.

517
00:18:28,306 --> 00:18:30,307
[Sam] So, Ian, if you're ready
for this next one...

518
00:18:30,308 --> 00:18:31,909
-[Ian] Yup.
-I'm gonna count you down.

519
00:18:31,910 --> 00:18:40,884
Three, two, one.

520
00:18:40,885 --> 00:18:42,186
[Michael] Whoa.

521
00:18:42,187 --> 00:18:45,489
[Marcie] So,
that was the decoder.

522
00:18:45,490 --> 00:18:46,690
Decoding his thoughts?

523
00:18:46,691 --> 00:18:48,325
-Decoding his thoughts.
-[Michael] Wow.

524
00:18:48,326 --> 00:18:50,561
[Marcie] Ian was in control
of the movements.

525
00:18:50,562 --> 00:18:52,329
[Michael] Nice work.

526
00:18:52,330 --> 00:18:54,264
 Already, Ian's achievements

527
00:18:54,265 --> 00:18:56,900
 go far beyond
 closing his hand.

528
00:18:56,901 --> 00:18:59,236
 With the help of this
 cutting-edge technology,

529
00:18:59,237 --> 00:19:01,371
 he can use
 his own paralyzed hand

530
00:19:01,372 --> 00:19:03,373
 to do a number
 of fine motor tasks

531
00:19:03,374 --> 00:19:06,210
 from everyday movements

532
00:19:06,211 --> 00:19:08,845
 to playing Guitar Hero.

533
00:19:08,846 --> 00:19:10,914
How many other people
are like Ian?

534
00:19:10,915 --> 00:19:13,317
Currently in the world,

535
00:19:13,318 --> 00:19:15,552
maybe five?

536
00:19:15,553 --> 00:19:18,789
[Michael] Ian continues
 to gain more independence

537
00:19:18,790 --> 00:19:21,725
 outside the lab, as well.

538
00:19:21,726 --> 00:19:23,660
Do people
ever drive with you

539
00:19:23,661 --> 00:19:25,662
and get nervous like,
"Oh, my gosh,

540
00:19:25,663 --> 00:19:27,497
well, clearly
this is dangerous."

541
00:19:27,498 --> 00:19:29,399
[Ian] I think
if everyone else

542
00:19:29,400 --> 00:19:30,767
that was driving
along in the road knew

543
00:19:30,768 --> 00:19:32,936
I have no use of my hands

544
00:19:32,937 --> 00:19:34,471
going 70 miles an hour
down the freeway,

545
00:19:34,472 --> 00:19:35,872
they may not like that.

546
00:19:35,873 --> 00:19:37,407
But they've-- they have
nothing to worry about.

547
00:19:37,408 --> 00:19:38,875
[Ian] Right, yeah,
and I'm probably safer

548
00:19:38,876 --> 00:19:41,011
because I can't take
my hands off the wheel

549
00:19:41,012 --> 00:19:43,380
-to get on my cell phone and...
-Right. Yup.

550
00:19:43,381 --> 00:19:45,249
You're not fiddling
with the radio and...

551
00:19:45,250 --> 00:19:47,284
Yeah, that I shouldn't be
doing while I'm driving.

552
00:19:47,285 --> 00:19:50,320
 [Michael] Ian's progress
 was truly inspiring,

553
00:19:50,321 --> 00:19:52,556
 and this was only
 the beginning for him.

554
00:19:52,557 --> 00:19:56,393
What are your hopes
for the future for yourself?

555
00:19:56,394 --> 00:19:59,296
[Ian] Hopefully,
I can upgrade

556
00:19:59,297 --> 00:20:01,765
to the next version
and, you know,

557
00:20:01,766 --> 00:20:03,033
have more capabilities

558
00:20:03,034 --> 00:20:05,902
and be able to do things
a lot easier.

559
00:20:05,903 --> 00:20:08,372
 In the long term, I hope
 that this can be a device

560
00:20:08,373 --> 00:20:10,040
 that people just use.

561
00:20:10,041 --> 00:20:12,276
 You have someone
 who has a spinal cord injury

562
00:20:12,277 --> 00:20:13,610
 and they can just continue

563
00:20:13,611 --> 00:20:15,279
 right where they left off.

564
00:20:15,280 --> 00:20:17,514
I think, you know,
the work that we're doing

565
00:20:17,515 --> 00:20:20,651
is something that has
never been done before

566
00:20:20,652 --> 00:20:31,361
and it's really exciting to be
on that cutting edge.

567
00:20:31,362 --> 00:20:33,463
Restoring movement
is one thing,

568
00:20:33,464 --> 00:20:35,732
but what about feeling,

569
00:20:35,733 --> 00:20:37,301
sensation?

570
00:20:37,302 --> 00:20:39,536
We feel with our skin
because of signals

571
00:20:39,537 --> 00:20:42,806
sent to the somatosensory
cortex of our brain.

572
00:20:42,807 --> 00:20:45,709
By putting sensors
in robotic fingers

573
00:20:45,710 --> 00:20:47,477
connected to implants
in a person's

574
00:20:47,478 --> 00:20:48,979
somatosensory cortex,

575
00:20:48,980 --> 00:20:50,981
researchers
at the University of Pittsburgh

576
00:20:50,982 --> 00:20:52,916
have enabled Nathan Copeland

577
00:20:52,917 --> 00:20:57,688
to feel
through a robotic hand.

578
00:20:57,689 --> 00:20:59,756
 Nathan underwent
 brain surgery

579
00:20:59,757 --> 00:21:01,491
 to receive two implants,

580
00:21:01,492 --> 00:21:02,926
 one in his motor cortex

581
00:21:02,927 --> 00:21:04,795
 to control a robotic arm

582
00:21:04,796 --> 00:21:05,929
 and a second implant

583
00:21:05,930 --> 00:21:08,598
 over his somatosensory cortex.

584
00:21:08,599 --> 00:21:09,800
 This second implant

585
00:21:09,801 --> 00:21:11,568
 stimulates his brain

586
00:21:11,569 --> 00:21:13,603
 and the pattern
 of stimulation depends

587
00:21:13,604 --> 00:21:15,639
 on what part
 of the robot hand is touched.

588
00:21:15,640 --> 00:21:18,575
 So, if you touch the robot
 on a specific finger,

589
00:21:18,576 --> 00:21:21,578
 then the part of Nathan's
 somatosensory cortex

590
00:21:21,579 --> 00:21:23,814
 that normally responds
 to that finger

591
00:21:23,815 --> 00:21:25,849
 get stimulated.

592
00:21:25,850 --> 00:21:27,951
[Nathan] Pinky.

593
00:21:27,952 --> 00:21:29,753
Uh, middle.

594
00:21:29,754 --> 00:21:33,056
[Michael] His brain interprets
 that as touch.

595
00:21:33,057 --> 00:21:35,926
 Nathan and Ian's
 remarkable achievements

596
00:21:35,927 --> 00:21:37,694
 have been aided
 by their ability

597
00:21:37,695 --> 00:21:39,996
 to communicate
 with the researchers involved.

598
00:21:39,997 --> 00:21:41,865
 But what can be done
 for people

599
00:21:41,866 --> 00:21:44,935
 who are not only
 unable to move,

600
00:21:44,936 --> 00:21:47,404
 but also unable to speak?

601
00:21:47,405 --> 00:21:49,539
 Steve Kaplan was an active

602
00:21:49,540 --> 00:21:52,776
 57-year-old computer programmer
 dating Laurie,

603
00:21:52,777 --> 00:21:55,078
 a horse wrangler
 for the rodeo.

604
00:21:55,079 --> 00:21:57,080
 But that all changed
 a year ago

605
00:21:57,081 --> 00:21:59,049
 when he suffered
 a massive stroke

606
00:21:59,050 --> 00:22:01,451
 leaving him
 in a vegetative state,

607
00:22:01,452 --> 00:22:03,687
 unable to move or speak.

608
00:22:03,688 --> 00:22:06,623
 Doctors initially declared
 Steve brain dead.

609
00:22:06,624 --> 00:22:08,558
 However, inside his body

610
00:22:08,559 --> 00:22:09,826
 he was fully conscious,

611
00:22:09,827 --> 00:22:11,962
 but unable to tell them so.

612
00:22:11,963 --> 00:22:13,864
 It wasn't
 until a nurse noticed

613
00:22:13,865 --> 00:22:16,600
 that Steve's eye movements
 were intentional

614
00:22:16,601 --> 00:22:19,736
 that he was diagnosed
 with locked-in syndrome,

615
00:22:19,737 --> 00:22:21,972
 a condition which robs
 people of everything

616
00:22:21,973 --> 00:22:23,707
 but their mind.

617
00:22:23,708 --> 00:22:26,576
 While a normal brain
 receives electrical signals

618
00:22:26,577 --> 00:22:29,045
 from the senses and sends
 signals back to them,

619
00:22:29,046 --> 00:22:31,581
 the stroke prevented
 the electrical signals

620
00:22:31,582 --> 00:22:34,184
 from leaving Steve's brain.

621
00:22:34,185 --> 00:22:35,986
 Over the last year,

622
00:22:35,987 --> 00:22:37,988
 with the help
 of physical therapists,

623
00:22:37,989 --> 00:22:39,856
 Steve has regained
 some very minor

624
00:22:39,857 --> 00:22:42,125
 range of motion in his neck.

625
00:22:42,126 --> 00:22:45,662
 I sat down with Steve
 and his now-wife Laurie

626
00:22:45,663 --> 00:22:47,964
 to learn more about
 locked-in syndrome.

627
00:22:47,965 --> 00:22:50,767
Steve, Laurie, hello.

628
00:22:50,768 --> 00:22:52,936
 Although he's still
 unable to speak,

629
00:22:52,937 --> 00:22:54,938
 thanks to new scientific
 developments,

630
00:22:54,939 --> 00:22:57,207
 Steve can communicate
 with the outside world

631
00:22:57,208 --> 00:22:58,909
 using a computer.

632
00:22:58,910 --> 00:23:00,677
[computer male voice]
 Hello, Michael.

633
00:23:00,678 --> 00:23:01,678
[Michael]
Nice to meet you, Steve.

634
00:23:01,679 --> 00:23:02,746
And nice
to meet you, Laurie.

635
00:23:02,747 --> 00:23:03,914
First of all,
thank you so much

636
00:23:03,915 --> 00:23:05,515
for giving us some time.

637
00:23:05,516 --> 00:23:08,452
Tell me how Steve started
being able to communicate.

638
00:23:08,453 --> 00:23:10,554
[Laurie] Well, you know,
I asked a lot of questions

639
00:23:10,555 --> 00:23:11,755
about locked-in syndrome

640
00:23:11,756 --> 00:23:13,056
when they explained
what it was,

641
00:23:13,057 --> 00:23:15,058
and there wasn't
a lot of answers.

642
00:23:15,059 --> 00:23:16,660
-Yeah.
-[Laurie] At the beginning,

643
00:23:16,661 --> 00:23:19,796
he would blink once for yes
and twice for no.

644
00:23:19,797 --> 00:23:22,866
 And that was the first parts
 of the communication.

645
00:23:22,867 --> 00:23:24,534
 And then they
 gave us a board,

646
00:23:24,535 --> 00:23:26,236
 and I went
 through the ABCs,

647
00:23:26,237 --> 00:23:27,737
 and he would close his eyes

648
00:23:27,738 --> 00:23:28,839
 when I got to what he wanted.

649
00:23:28,840 --> 00:23:29,973
 I'd write it down,

650
00:23:29,974 --> 00:23:31,508
 and that's how it began.

651
00:23:31,509 --> 00:23:33,109
[Michael] As you could imagine,

652
00:23:33,110 --> 00:23:35,679
 Laurie and Steve's
 first method of communicating

653
00:23:35,680 --> 00:23:38,915
 was a slow
 and painstaking process.

654
00:23:38,916 --> 00:23:40,817
 But just months later,

655
00:23:40,818 --> 00:23:42,519
 an engineer working to help

656
00:23:42,520 --> 00:23:43,720
 locked-in patients

657
00:23:43,721 --> 00:23:44,955
 built Steve a machine

658
00:23:44,956 --> 00:23:46,923
 that tracks his eye movements.

659
00:23:46,924 --> 00:23:49,993
 As Steve looks at different
 letters on a screen,

660
00:23:49,994 --> 00:23:52,529
 the machine translates
 where he's looking

661
00:23:52,530 --> 00:23:54,664
 into synthesized
 audible speech.

662
00:23:54,665 --> 00:23:56,533
[computer male voice]
 I want to recover.

663
00:23:56,534 --> 00:23:59,102
[Michael] Although
 there's still a slight delay

664
00:23:59,103 --> 00:24:01,037
 in communication
 as Steve scans

665
00:24:01,038 --> 00:24:02,706
 the letters on the screen,

666
00:24:02,707 --> 00:24:04,541
 this method is much more fluid

667
00:24:04,542 --> 00:24:10,113
 and significantly faster.

668
00:24:10,114 --> 00:24:12,516
The computer helps me
communicate

669
00:24:12,517 --> 00:24:14,618
[Michael] Yeah.
You can write with your eyes.

670
00:24:14,619 --> 00:24:15,819
[Laurie]
This thing's amazing.

671
00:24:15,820 --> 00:24:18,021
He can email,
he can text,

672
00:24:18,022 --> 00:24:19,523
call me
if he needs something.

673
00:24:19,524 --> 00:24:20,857
It's such a relief.

674
00:24:20,858 --> 00:24:21,925
[computer male voice]
 It does wonders.

675
00:24:21,926 --> 00:24:23,593
[Michael]
It does wonders, yes.

676
00:24:23,594 --> 00:24:24,794
-Uh-hmm, [chuckles]
-[Michael] And I could only

677
00:24:24,795 --> 00:24:26,696
imagine how emotional
it would have been

678
00:24:26,697 --> 00:24:29,132
to you to be able to look
and write a thing,

679
00:24:29,133 --> 00:24:30,600
and then have it spoken.

680
00:24:30,601 --> 00:24:33,036
And, Laurie,
for you to hear

681
00:24:33,037 --> 00:24:35,906
words coming from his mind,
from his heart,

682
00:24:35,907 --> 00:24:37,607
especially
for the first time

683
00:24:37,608 --> 00:24:39,175
-in a long time.
-[Laurie] Yes.

684
00:24:39,176 --> 00:24:47,584
What was the first thing
you said, Steve?

685
00:24:47,585 --> 00:24:49,586
[computer male voice] The first
 message was happy birthday.

686
00:24:49,587 --> 00:24:51,855
[laughter]

687
00:24:51,856 --> 00:24:53,056
What a birthday present.

688
00:24:53,057 --> 00:24:54,858
[Laurie laughs]
It really was.

689
00:24:54,859 --> 00:24:57,160
[Michael] Steve's progress
 is remarkable,

690
00:24:57,161 --> 00:24:58,895
 and it would be
 difficult to deny

691
00:24:58,896 --> 00:25:01,197
 the connection between
 his new ability to communicate

692
00:25:01,198 --> 00:25:02,933
 and connect
 with the outside world

693
00:25:02,934 --> 00:25:04,634
 with the incredible advances

694
00:25:04,635 --> 00:25:06,970
 he's made physically
 over the last year.

695
00:25:06,971 --> 00:25:09,039
-Look up at the ceiling.
-[Michael] Yeah.

696
00:25:09,040 --> 00:25:12,008
-Look down at your thumbs.
-[clears throat]

697
00:25:12,009 --> 00:25:13,944
Look over at me,
your beautiful wife.

698
00:25:13,945 --> 00:25:15,712
[laughter]

699
00:25:15,713 --> 00:25:17,881
[Michael] Laurie and Steve
 hope that one day

700
00:25:17,882 --> 00:25:19,349
 Steve will make
 a full recovery

701
00:25:19,350 --> 00:25:26,656
 from locked-in syndrome.

702
00:25:26,657 --> 00:25:29,626
Steve's eye-tracking device
is electric,

703
00:25:29,627 --> 00:25:31,027
and so is his brain.

704
00:25:31,028 --> 00:25:32,629
They're connected by the fact

705
00:25:32,630 --> 00:25:34,631
that Steve can move his eyes.

706
00:25:34,632 --> 00:25:36,199
But some locked-in patients

707
00:25:36,200 --> 00:25:38,969
can't even control
their eye movements.

708
00:25:38,970 --> 00:25:40,203
They have what is known

709
00:25:40,204 --> 00:25:43,773
as completely
locked-in syndrome.

710
00:25:43,774 --> 00:25:46,242
For these patients,
the eye-tracking technology

711
00:25:46,243 --> 00:25:49,279
that helped Steve communicate
is useless.

712
00:25:49,280 --> 00:25:51,781
 But researchers in Europe
 recently found a way

713
00:25:51,782 --> 00:25:53,984
 of allowing completely
 locked-in patients

714
00:25:53,985 --> 00:25:57,387
 to communicate
 using just their thoughts.

715
00:25:57,388 --> 00:25:59,656
 The researchers combined EEG

716
00:25:59,657 --> 00:26:02,325
 with near-infrared
 spectroscopy,

717
00:26:02,326 --> 00:26:03,927
 which can non-invasively

718
00:26:03,928 --> 00:26:06,096
 measure blood flow
 in the brain.

719
00:26:06,097 --> 00:26:07,230
The patients were asked

720
00:26:07,231 --> 00:26:08,932
simple yes or no questions

721
00:26:08,933 --> 00:26:10,900
that the researchers
knew the answers to,

722
00:26:10,901 --> 00:26:13,770
which allowed them
to train a machine to recognize

723
00:26:13,771 --> 00:26:15,939
which brain signals meant yes

724
00:26:15,940 --> 00:26:18,274
and which brain signals
meant no.

725
00:26:18,275 --> 00:26:20,343
The researchers
then asked the patients

726
00:26:20,344 --> 00:26:21,845
a new set of questions

727
00:26:21,846 --> 00:26:22,979
they knew the answer to,

728
00:26:22,980 --> 00:26:24,414
and using just their thoughts,

729
00:26:24,415 --> 00:26:26,149
 the patients were able to give

730
00:26:26,150 --> 00:26:29,786
 the correct answers
 to 70% of the questions.

731
00:26:29,787 --> 00:26:32,288
Now, giving just
yes or no answers

732
00:26:32,289 --> 00:26:33,423
may be limited,

733
00:26:33,424 --> 00:26:35,158
but this technology is new.

734
00:26:35,159 --> 00:26:37,927
All of this happened
just this year.

735
00:26:37,928 --> 00:26:39,829
 These rapid advancements,

736
00:26:39,830 --> 00:26:43,233
 thanks to the devotion
 and effort of researchers

737
00:26:43,234 --> 00:26:44,901
 and subjects around the world,

738
00:26:44,902 --> 00:26:46,736
 are slowly but surely

739
00:26:46,737 --> 00:26:49,739
 chipping away
 at the mysteries of the mind.

740
00:26:49,740 --> 00:26:51,274
The better
we understand the mind,

741
00:26:51,275 --> 00:26:52,809
the better
we'll be able to help

742
00:26:52,810 --> 00:26:54,444
the millions of people
who struggle to do

743
00:26:54,445 --> 00:26:56,813
what they want
because of psychological

744
00:26:56,814 --> 00:26:58,448
or neurological conditions,

745
00:26:58,449 --> 00:27:03,019
and ultimately the better
we'll understand ourselves.

746
00:27:03,020 --> 00:27:04,888
And as always,

747
00:27:04,889 --> 00:27:08,191
thanks for watching.

748
00:27:08,192 --> 00:27:11,129
[theme music playing]

